I can see exactly what's wrong. There are **two bugs** causing the missing color fill:

**Bug 1 — `data` starts empty and never triggers reactivity in the Map.** In `App.svelte`, you push into the `data` array with `data.push(geo[i])` inside `onMount`. Svelte can't detect mutations to arrays — it only reacts to reassignment. So `Map` receives an empty array and never re-renders when the data loads.

**Bug 2 — The `geooverlay` paths render on top of the filled paths**, covering them with a `fill: none` stroke — but since SVG default fill is `black`, any path without an explicit `fill` attribute will fill black. Your overlay paths don't have `fill="none"` in the `<path>` element itself (only in the CSS class), which may cause rendering issues depending on browser.

Here are the exact fixes:

---

### Fix 1 — `App.svelte`: trigger reactivity after data load

Find this line at the end of your `onMount` data loop:
```js
data.push(geo[i]);
```
And the line after the loop:
```js
fullData = [...data];
```

Replace the whole loop + assignment with:
```js
// collect into a local array first, then assign once
let built = [];
for (let i = 0; i < geo.length; i++) {
  // ... all your existing join logic stays the same ...
  built.push(geo[i]);
}
data = built;        // ← reassignment triggers Svelte reactivity
fullData = [...built];
```

The key is: **never mutate `data` with `.push()` — always reassign it.**

---

### Fix 2 — `Map.svelte`: add `fill="none"` directly on the overlay `<path>`

Change:
```svelte
{#each fullData as d}
  <path class="geooverlay" d={path(d)}/>
{/each}
```

To:
```svelte
{#each fullData as d}
  <path class="geooverlay" d={path(d)} fill="none"/>
{/each}
```

SVG inline `fill` attributes override CSS, so this guarantees the overlay never accidentally covers your colored fills.

---

### Fix 3 (bonus) — `Map.svelte`: make the legend reactive

Your legend block uses:
```js
$: {
  const colorLegend = legendColor()...
  d3.select(legend).call(colorLegend);
}
```

This won't fire on first mount because `legend` (the bound DOM node) is `undefined` until after render. Add a guard:

```js
$: if (legend) {
  const colorLegend = legendColor()
    .shape('rect')
    .cells(11)
    .scale(scale);
  d3.select(legend).call(colorLegend);
}
```

---

After these three fixes, the map should color correctly. Try them and paste back any new error messages or console output — we can move on to adding the score-type selector (WVS raw vs updated vs LLM) once the map is rendering.

