content.text:
 The cancel bug is here — your brush has two separate handlers:

```js
.on("brush", brushed)   // fires while dragging
.on("end", brushended)  // fires when released
```

When you **clear** the brush (click without dragging), only `brushended` fires with `selection: null`, which correctly sets `filter = []` and calls `update()`. That part is fine.

The real problem is that the `brush` object is created **once at module load time** with `.on("brush", brushed)` — but `brushed` closes over `xScale` which doesn't exist yet. More critically, the `$:` block that calls `d3.select(brushLayer).call(brush)` **re-calls the brush every time any reactive variable changes**, which resets the brush visual and can interfere with clearing.

The fix is to separate brush setup (once, in `onMount`) from axis updates (reactive):

```svelte
<script>
    import * as d3 from 'd3';
    import { onMount } from 'svelte';

    export let data;
    export let fullData;
    export let variable;
    export let filter;
    export let update;

    let margin = {top: 10, right: 30, bottom: 30, left: 40};
    let width = 360;
    let height = 200;
    let chartW = width - margin.left - margin.right;
    let chartH = height - margin.top - margin.bottom;

    let brushLayer;
    let xAxis;
    let yAxis;

    $: xScale = d3.scaleLinear()
        .range([0, chartW])
        .domain(d3.extent(fullData.map(d => d.properties[variable])));

    $: binData = d3.histogram()
        .value(d => d.properties[variable])
        .domain(xScale.domain())
        .thresholds(xScale.ticks(30));

    $: backgroundBins = binData(fullData);
    $: bins = binData(data);

    $: yScale = d3.scaleLinear()
        .range([chartH, 0])
        .domain([0, d3.max(backgroundBins, d => d.length)]);

    // axes update reactively, but brush is set up only once
    $: if (xAxis) d3.select(xAxis).call(d3.axisBottom(xScale));
    $: if (yAxis) d3.select(yAxis).call(d3.axisLeft(yScale));

    onMount(() => {
        const brush = d3.brushX()
            .extent([[0, 0], [chartW, chartH]])
            .on("brush", (event) => {
                if (event.selection) {
                    // read xScale reactively at call time, not at setup time
                    filter = [
                        xScale.invert(event.selection[0]),
                        xScale.invert(event.selection[1])
                    ];
                    update();
                }
            })
            .on("end", (event) => {
                if (!event.selection) {
                    filter = [];
                    update(); // this now hits the else branch → clears selectedCountries
                }
            });

        d3.select(brushLayer).call(brush);
    });
</script>
```

The template and styles stay exactly the same. The key changes:

- `onMount` sets up the brush **once** so clearing it doesn't get disrupted by reactive re-renders
- The `brush`/`end` callbacks are inline arrow functions so they read `xScale` at call time (always current)
- Axes update via separate `$: if (xAxis)` guards instead of being bundled with the brush call

