 The issue is that `.map` has `flex-grow: 1` which makes it expand and push the scatterplot out. Since you've switched to a row layout for the top, the map is growing horizontally and overflowing.

Two minimal fixes:

1. Constrain the map's width explicitly
2. Make the top row's children not overflow

```svelte
<style>
  .layout-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    height: 100%;
    gap: 5px;
    padding: 15px;
  }

  .row-top {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: row;
    flex: 2 1 0;
    gap: 5px;
    min-width: 0;        /* prevent row from overflowing */
  }

  .row-bottom {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: row;
    flex: 1 1 0;
    gap: 5px;
  }

  .row-top > div,
  .row-bottom > div {
    padding: 8px;
  }

  .controls {
    flex: 0 0 auto;      /* don't grow or shrink */
  }

  .map {
    flex: 1 1 0;         /* grow to fill, but respect siblings */
    min-width: 0;        /* prevent overflow */
  }

  .scatter {
    flex: 0 0 auto;      /* don't push out */
    min-width: 0;
  }

  .hist {
    flex: 1 1 0;
    min-width: 0;
  }
</style>
```

The critical fix is `min-width: 0` on `.map` and the `.row-top` container. By default, flex children have `min-width: auto`, which means they refuse to shrink below their content size — that's what was pushing the scatterplot out of bounds. Setting `min-width: 0` allows them to shrink properly within the row.

