chat_messages.text:
 Yes! That's a great crossfiltering interaction. Here's how to implement it:

## Clicking a Country on the Map → Highlights in All 3 Histograms

The idea is:
1. Store the selected country in a shared Svelte store (or prop)
2. On map click, update that selection
3. Each histogram reads the selection and highlights the corresponding bar

### Shared Store

```js
// stores.js
import { writable } from 'svelte/store';
export const selectedCountry = writable(null);
```

### Map Component — on click, set the selection

```svelte
<!-- ChoroplethMap.svelte -->
<script>
  import { selectedCountry } from './stores.js';
</script>

<path
  on:click={() => selectedCountry.set(d.properties.name)}
  ...
/>
```

### Histogram Component — highlight the selected country's bar

In each histogram, you need to find **which bin** the selected country falls into, then highlight that bin.

```svelte
<!-- Histogram.svelte -->
<script>
  import { selectedCountry } from './stores.js';
  import { derived } from 'svelte/store';

  export let data;       // full dataset
  export let variable;   // e.g. "gdp", "population"

  // Find the value for the selected country
  $: selectedValue = $selectedCountry
    ? data.find(d => d.name === $selectedCountry)?.[variable]
    : null;

  // Find which bin it falls into
  $: highlightedBin = selectedValue != null
    ? bins.find(bin => selectedValue >= bin.x0 && selectedValue < bin.x1)
    : null;
</script>

{#each bins as bin}
  <rect
    class:highlighted={bin === highlightedBin}
    ...
  />
{/each}

<style>
  rect { fill: steelblue; }
  rect.highlighted { fill: orange; }
</style>
```

### What the user sees

When you click a country on the map, all three histograms will **highlight the bar** that contains that country's value — so you can instantly see where it falls in the distribution of GDP, population, life expectancy, etc.

### Bonus: Add a vertical line instead of (or in addition to) highlighting

```svelte
{#if selectedValue != null}
  <line
    x1={xScale(selectedValue)} x2={xScale(selectedValue)}
    y1={0} y2={height}
    stroke="orange" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="4"
  />
{/if}
```

This adds a dashed vertical line showing exactly where the selected country sits, which is even more precise than bar highlighting. Both together work really well visually.

The key is the **shared Svelte store** — it's the glue that lets the map and all three histograms stay in sync reactively without passing props up and down.

