\section{Results}
\label{results}
We present the results from our belief network analysis in the following order. First, we examine wave-level structural patterns across countries. Second, we present snapshots of belief system clustering results by wave. Third, we examine the thematic organization of structural hubs within clustered belief networks and how these themes evolve across waves. Finally, we explore country-level trajectories in theme composition and the geographic patterns of cluster membership.

\subsection{Wave-Level Structural Patterns}

This section examines global structural patterns in belief networks across waves, focusing on two features: cross-country structural divergence and the role of religiosity as a structural hub.

\textbf{First, belief systems are becoming more diverging.}
Table~\ref{tab:wave_summary} summarizes structural heterogeneity across all seven waves. Average overlap in high-betweenness beliefs ranges from 13.6\% to 34.6\%. Notably, overlap remains consistently low as the number of sampled countries increases (13.6--16.1\% in Waves 4--7, $N = 41$--66 countries). This persistent low overlap indicates that countries organize their belief systems around different axes of differentiation. When two countries share higher overlap, their societies tend to be structured around similar tensions or contested issues.

Figure~\ref{fig:overlap_trend} illustrates the relationship between cross-country overlap and sample size across waves. Each bubble represents a wave; bubble size indicates the number of sampled countries and color indicates the average overlap ratio of the top ten bridge beliefs across all country pairs. Despite the expansion of sampled countries beginning in Wave 3, cross-country structural similarity remains limited, reinforcing the observation that belief systems are organized differently across national contexts.

One notable exception is Wave 3, which shows a relatively high overlap ratio (25\%) despite having a comparable number of sampled countries ($N = 55$) to later waves ($N = 41$--66). As discussed in the Methods section, the number of survey items varies across waves. We therefore examine whether the elevated overlap in Wave 3 may be driven by questionnaire differences.

\begin{figure}[!h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=12cm]{images/overlap_with_sample_size.png}
    \caption{Cross-country overlap in bridge beliefs across waves. Bubble size represents the number of sampled countries.}
    \label{fig:overlap_trend}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:overlap_v_items} compares the average overlap ratio with the number of survey items across waves. The results show that the Wave 3 convergence occurs despite the expansion of questionnaire items in later waves, suggesting that the observed pattern is unlikely to be driven by measurement differences.

\begin{figure}[!h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=12cm]{images/panel_c_overlap_vs_items.png}
    \caption{Average overlap ratio (red) and number of survey items (blue) across waves.}
    \label{fig:overlap_v_items}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Second, religiosity emerges as a major structural hub.}  
Across all seven waves, religiosity-related items frequently appear among the most central beliefs, consistently occupying high-betweenness positions that bridge moral, social, and political attitudes. Although the exact rankings vary across countries and waves, this pattern persists, highlighting the structural role of religiosity rather than its absolute prominence within any single country.  

Figure~\ref{fig:top30_bc} illustrates this pattern for Wave 7, showing the global top 30 items ranked by average betweenness centrality (see Appendix~\ref{appendix_top30} for analogous figures for all seven waves). The y-axis displays item content, dots are colored by theme, and error bars represent the 95\% confidence interval. Items such as belief in God, the importance of God in one’s life, and belief in heaven or hell repeatedly occupy bridging positions across waves.  

The structural importance of religiosity varies by context. An item attains high BC when it serves as an axis of differentiation, even if religiosity itself is relatively homogeneous within a society. In countries with low variation in religious commitment, these items tend to be more structurally peripheral, suggesting that centrality reflects relational importance within the belief network rather than absolute prevalence. Examining the top-ranked items across all seven waves, non-religiosity items occasionally appear: Wave 1 (political scale self-positioning), Wave 4 (justifiability of homosexuality), and Wave 5 (information source: internet/email). Otherwise, religiosity-related items dominate, indicating that structural centrality does not necessarily track temporal prominence.

\begin{figure}[!h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=15cm]{images/top30_bc_wave7.png}
    \caption{Wave 7 top 30 items ranked by global average betweenness centrality with 95\% CI.}
    \label{fig:top30_bc}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Structural Snapshots Within Wave}

To further examine patterns of belief systems across countries, we cluster countries based on the structure of their belief networks, following method discussed in section \ref{cluster_characterization}.

\textbf{Overview of Clustering Patterns}

Table \ref{tab:cluster_summary} summarizes clustering results across the seven waves. We focus on Waves 3–7, given the limited number of participating countries in Waves 1 and 2. At Wave 3, the belief systems converge into 4 clusters, despite the substantial increase in sampled countries (55 countries), indicating a genuine structural alignment rather than a sampling artifact. Wave 4 exhibits further convergence with only 3 clusters, suggesting a temporary convergence of the global belief network.

\begin{table}[!h]
\centering
\caption{Cluster-Level Summary Across WVS Waves}
\label{tab:cluster_summary}
\begin{tabular}{lrrrrrr}
\toprule
Wave & Countries & K & Silhouette & Avg. Ov. & Max Ov. & Min Ov. \\
\midrule
1 & 8  & 2  & 0.119 & 34.64 & 50 & 10 \\
2 & 18 & 7  & 0.169 & 13.86 & 50 & 0  \\
3 & 55 & 4  & 0.067 & 23.73 & 70 & 0  \\
4 & 41 & 3  & 0.091 & 15.49 & 70 & 0  \\
5 & 58 & 10 & 0.094 & 16.06 & 70 & 0  \\
6 & 60 & 10 & 0.095 & 13.88 & 80 & 0  \\
7 & 66 & 9  & 0.078 & 13.60 & 50 & 0  \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\vspace{0.5em}
\begin{minipage}{\textwidth}
\small
\textit{Notes:} Optimal K is the number of clusters determined via silhouette score maximization. Average, maximum, and minimum overlaps indicate the proportion of shared top-10 high-betweenness items between all country pairs within each wave. Waves 1 and 2 have limited country coverage; interpretation of clustering patterns focuses on Waves 3--7.
\end{minipage}
\end{table}

From Wave 4 onward, divergence re-emerges. The number of clusters increases substantially (10 clusters in Waves 5 and 6, 9 clusters in Wave 7), while average overlap declines (from 23.7\% in Wave 3 to 13.6\% in Wave 7). This pattern indicates that belief systems progressively differentiate across countries, reflecting growing heterogeneity in how beliefs are organized globally.

Notably, silhouette scores remain relatively low across these waves (0.067–0.095), consistent with the presence of multiple moderately separated clusters rather than sharply distinct groupings. Maximum overlap within some pairs can still reach high values (up to 80\%), implying that certain countries share highly similar structures even in later waves. Overall, the cluster trajectory highlights a dynamic process of convergence followed by renewed divergence, capturing both the temporary alignment and subsequent diversification of global belief systems.

\textbf{The Wave 4 Turning Point}

Cluster counts indicate that after Wave 4, the number of clusters increases, signaling renewed structural differentiation. To investigate whether Wave 4 represents a structural turning point, we examined multiple network-level metrics.

Figure~\ref{fig:wave4_turn} shows that several indicators simultaneously reach their minimum values at Wave 4. The number of clusters reaches its lowest observed value of 3, indicating a temporary convergence of belief networks across countries. Distinctiveness also attains a minimum of 3.59, suggesting that clusters were less differentiated from one another at this wave. Similarly, within-cluster variation falls to 16.98, implying that countries within the same cluster were more structurally similar to each other.

In Wave 5, all three metrics rise, reflecting structural fragmentation. The number of clusters rises to 10, mean distinctiveness increases to 9.85, and mean within-cluster variation reaches 20.00. Together, these changes indicate that belief systems become more structurally differentiated after Wave 4: countries are divided into a larger number of cluster types, these clusters are more distinct from one another, and countries within the same cluster exhibit greater internal variation. For Waves 6 and 7, none of the indicators return to the low levels observed at Wave 4. The simultaneous minima across these measures at Wave 4 suggest a temporary alignment of belief systems across countries, consistent with a structural turning point. The combination of fewer clusters, lower distinctiveness, and reduced within-cluster variation indicates that global belief networks were more coherent and less fragmented before diverging again in subsequent waves.

\begin{figure}[!h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[scale = 0.6]{images/wave4_inflection_multimetric.png}
    \caption{Wave 4 $\rightarrow$ Wave 5 is the turning point point}
    \label{fig:wave4_turn}
\end{figure}

We examine the evolution of belief system structures using boxplots of distinctiveness (Figure \ref{fig:distinctiveness_dist}) and within-cluster variation in structural importance, as operationalized by BC's standard deviation (Figure \ref{fig:cluster_variation_dist}). Distinctiveness captures how much an item structurally differentiates its cluster from others, while within-cluster variation measures the universality of an item’s structural role within a cluster. High within-cluster variation indicates that an item bridges beliefs in some countries but not others, whereas low within-cluster variation reflects consistent structural importance across all cluster members. Similarly, high distinctiveness signals that an item is a key differentiator of cluster identity, while low distinctiveness indicates that it is common across clusters.

\begin{figure}[!h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width = 12cm]{images/boxplot_distinctiveness.png}
    \caption{Distinctiveness distribution across seven waves}
    \label{fig:distinctiveness_dist}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[!h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width = 12cm]{images/boxplot_variation.png}
    \caption{Within-cluster variation distribution across seven waves}
    \label{fig:cluster_variation_dist}
\end{figure}


Early waves (1–2) display a hierarchical pattern. Mean within-cluster variation peaks at 25.1 in Wave 1 and 20.6 in Wave 2, with wide interquartile ranges and several extreme outliers, indicating that bridge items are not universally important within clusters. Countries sharing the same thematic label implement it through different structural architectures. At the same time, cluster distinctiveness reaches a maximum in Wave 2 (mean 11.1), with many high outliers, showing that clusters are sharply differentiated from one another. These observations are consistent with a hierarchical differentiation in which structural roles are concentrated: few clusters exist, each structurally distinct, and bridging is driven by a small number of exceptional items.

Waves 3–4 mark a period of convergence. Both within-cluster variation and distinctiveness decline to their minima (std $\approx$ 16.98, distinctiveness $\approx$ 3.59 in Wave 4), with boxplots showing narrow interquartile ranges and minimal outliers. Within clusters, items now play more universal roles, and clusters differ little from one another structurally. This convergence reflects a flattening of the belief network: countries share both thematic and structural patterns, and exceptional bridging items are largely absent. Wave 4 therefore represents an inflection point where universality and differentiation are simultaneously minimized.

In Waves 5–7, the pattern shifts again, but in a manner distinct from the early hierarchical configuration. Mean within-cluster variation rebounds to 20–21, and many outliers appear, indicating that items are less consistently important within clusters. Mean distinctiveness rises moderately (7.7–9.8) but remains below the Wave 2 peak, and outliers are now densely clustered rather than isolated extremes. These observations suggest a form of distributed structural complexity: clusters proliferate (9–10 in Waves 5–7) and share thematic labels, yet the implementation of beliefs is different across countries. Structural differentiation is driven by many moderately exceptional items rather than a few common dominant bridges, creating diversity spread across the network rather than concentrated in specific items or clusters. Importantly, this pattern shows that more clusters do not necessarily correspond to sharper structural differences, highlighting the emergence of a more flexible, networked form of diversity.

Taken together, the boxplots reveal an arc of structural change consistent with, but distinct from, the occurrence–centrality patterns. Early belief systems exhibit hierarchical differentiation with concentrated bridging and heterogeneous implementations within clusters. Middle waves converge toward universal patterns, minimizing structural differentiation both within and between clusters. Later waves display distributed complexity, with many clusters and widespread exceptional items producing networked diversity. This trajectory illustrates that contemporary structural diversity is not a return to hierarchical differentiation, but a qualitatively new configuration in which thematic proliferation coexists with softer boundaries and heterogeneous structural roles across countries.


\section{Introduction}
\label{intro}
\subsection{Motivation}
The growing salience of nationalist and populist discourses in the past decade stands in striking contrast to the decades-long trajectory of globalization that once promised, or at least was imagined to bring, greater cultural integration and cosmopolitanism. Despite unprecedented connectedness through global social platforms and the increasingly complex networks that support the global production and consumption of both tangible and intangible goods, individuals today appear ever more confined within ideologically homogeneous spaces, both algorithmically and by choice. This growing gap between material interconnectedness and cultural insularity raises an empirical question at the heart of this project: have societies across the globe truly become more similar in their values, or are we witnessing renewed divergence beneath the surface of globalization?

Understanding this paradox requires situating contemporary developments within the longer trajectory of modernization. Modernization theory is primarily concerned with explaining and predicting the process and outcome of countries entering post-industrial phase of development. Yet, countries experience these transitions unevenly in terms of scale, onset time, and duration. Building on this observation, scholars have developed competing frameworks. The post-materialist theory suggests that economic security leads to a shift toward self-expression and autonomy. World society theory emphasizes the diffusion and homogenization of global cultural models. Multiple modernities theory highlights diverse, context-dependent pathways of change. To test these ideas, researchers have relied heavily on longitudinal survey data such as the World Values Survey (WVS) to analyze values and their social manifestations. However, while longitudinal surveys are designed to be comprehensive and consists of a wealth of questions, only a relatively limited set of indicators are selected for analysis. This practice inevitably invites concerns on an implicit bias, which assumes significance of and interpretations on values according to preconceived norms and potentially overlooks other culturally salient domains of belief.

This project adopts an emergent, bottom-up approach to overcome such constraints. By not starting with predefined categories of belief, it avoids imposing externally derived schemas onto the data and instead lets culturally salient value patterns surface directly from respondents’ answers. At the same time, a relational analytic framework shifts attention from the specific content of attitudes to the ways people organize and connect those attitudes in their thinking. Instead of treating values as isolated items, this approach maps how beliefs cohere, cluster, and structure one another within cultural contexts. By examining these patterned relationships, the project uncovers the cultural logics that organize belief systems and traces how these configurations evolve across countries and over time. This study advances a more inclusive view of modernization and globalization as processes shaped by diverse and evolving cultural logics.

\subsection{Research Questions}
I propose the following research questions to navigate this project:
\begin{itemize}
    \item How are belief systems structurally organized within countries? Do they tend to revolve around a single dominant organizing belief or multiple organizing beliefs?

    \item How do the organizing beliefs that anchor national belief systems vary across countries? Which countries exhibit similar structural configurations of organizing beliefs, and which differ?

    \item How do organizing beliefs evolve over time? Within the clusters identified at each wave, which beliefs gain or lose brokerage power, and how do cluster distinctiveness and within-cluster variation change longitudinally?

    \item To what extent do globally shared organizing beliefs remain stable across waves, and where do we observe shifts in the dominant themes structuring belief systems?
\end{itemize}

