**Issue-Specific Evolution: Digital Technology**

The transformation of belief systems can be further illustrated through the case of digital technology. Unlike the homosexuality item, which is captured by a consistent survey question across waves, digital-related items evolve alongside the technology itself. Table~\ref{tab:digital_items} lists the candidate items analyzed, divided into two types: information access items, which capture how people use digital technology to obtain information, and political digital items, which capture how people use digital technology to participate in political life. Because no single item spans all three waves, we treat any item of each type appearing as a cluster-characterizing item as evidence that digital technology functions as a structural hub in that society's belief system at that wave.

\begin{table}[!h]
\centering
\caption{Digital Items Analyzed by Wave and Type}
\label{tab:digital_items}
... [item table here]
\end{table}

Figure~\ref{fig:digital_share} shows the share of clusters in which digital items are cluster-characterizing across Waves 5, 6, and 7, separately for information access and political digital items. The pattern for information access items reveals a clear arc of emergence and contraction. In Wave 5 (2005--2009), information access items are structurally central in five out of ten clusters — a remarkably broad presence spanning societies at very different levels of development. By Wave 6 (2010--2014), this share declines to two out of ten clusters. By Wave 7 (2017--2022), information access items appear in only one out of nine clusters. Political digital items, absent in Waves 5 and 6, appear in three out of nine clusters in Wave 7, indicating the emergence of a new digital axis organized around political participation rather than information access.

\begin{figure}[!h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=12cm]{images/digital_cluster_share.png}
    \caption{Share of clusters with digital items as structural hubs by wave and type.}
    \label{fig:digital_share}
\end{figure}

Table~\ref{tab:digital_countries} details which countries drive these patterns at each wave. In Wave 5, information access items are central across a wide range of societies — Western developed countries (United States, Canada, Australia, Western Europe), Latin America (Argentina, Chile, Colombia, Mexico), Eastern Europe (Bulgaria, Romania, Russia, Slovenia), and parts of Asia and Africa (China, Indonesia, South Korea, Zambia). This breadth reflects the historical moment at which internet access was becoming widespread but remained sufficiently uneven within societies to function as a powerful axis of differentiation, connecting attitudes toward information, institutions, and civic participation in ways that distinguished belief groups from one another. Notably, even at this early stage, the item organizes distinct clusters of countries: Western democracies form one cluster, Southern European and Latin American countries another, and a third grouping includes China, Iran, and Serbia — contexts where internet access was politically contested from the outset.

By Wave 6, the country list contracts substantially. Western developed countries where internet access had become near-universal begin to drop out, consistent with the axis-of-differentiation logic: when a behavior becomes sufficiently widespread within a society, it loses its power to differentiate belief groups and recedes from structural centrality. The item itself shifts from internet and email as information sources to PC use frequency, reflecting both the evolution of the survey instrument and the changing nature of digital differentiation.

Wave 7 presents the most striking pattern. Information access items remain structurally central in only six societies — China, Indonesia, Japan, Myanmar, Peru, and Taiwan — concentrated almost entirely in East and Southeast Asia. The item driving this clustering is social media use, indicating that the axis of digital differentiation has shifted from whether people access the internet at all to how they engage with it socially. The concentration in Asian contexts is theoretically suggestive: these are societies where the relationship between digital platforms, information access, and political life remains actively contested, making social media a powerful structural connector across belief domains.

\begin{table}[!h]
\centering
\caption{Countries with Digital Items as Structural Hubs by Wave and Type}
\label{tab:digital_countries}
... [country table here]
\end{table}

\textbf{Digital Technology and Political Mobilization}

In Wave 7, the digital axis takes on an additional dimension. Beyond information access, items measuring political actions using the internet emerge as cluster-characterizing in a broader set of societies. Two patterns are immediately visible. First, the six countries where social media is central are also the six countries where political internet searching is central — the overlap is complete. In these societies, digital technology organizes belief systems comprehensively, connecting information access, social media use, and political participation into a single structural axis. Second, political internet searching is additionally central in nineteen further countries, spanning established democracies (Germany, Greece), Latin American societies (Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador), and more restricted political contexts (Iran, Vietnam, Kazakhstan). What unites these otherwise diverse societies is not regime type or development level, but the salience of digital political participation as a contested or emerging issue — one that connects attitudes toward institutions, trust, and civic engagement in ways that restructure the belief system architecture.

Taken together, the trajectory of digital items illustrates two features of the axis-of-differentiation dynamic. First, the nature of what makes digital technology structurally central shifts as the technology itself evolves and diffuses — from access in Wave 5, to engagement in Wave 6, to social and political use in Wave 7. Second, as digital access normalizes in developed societies, it recedes as a structural hub there while remaining or becoming central in contexts where the relationship between digital technology and political life is still being negotiated. This pattern complements the homosexuality case: both illustrate how globally diffusing issues become structural hubs at different moments and through different mechanisms across societies, rather than following a single developmental sequence. The digital case further demonstrates that the axis of differentiation itself can shift in nature — not just in which societies it organizes, but in what aspect of a phenomenon becomes the fault line around which beliefs cohere.

